            <section class="prose text-sm">
              <h2>How the corticosteroid conversion is calculated</h2>
              <p>
                Most systemic glucocorticoids can be compared using their
                <strong>relative anti‑inflammatory potency</strong>. A widely
                used reference set is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-mono">
                  20&nbsp;mg hydrocortisone ≈ 25&nbsp;mg cortisone acetate ≈
                  5&nbsp;mg prednisone ≈ 5&nbsp;mg prednisolone ≈ 4&nbsp;mg
                  methylprednisolone ≈ 4&nbsp;mg triamcinolone ≈ 0.75&nbsp;mg
                  dexamethasone ≈ 0.75&nbsp;mg betamethasone
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                In this calculator we treat
                <strong>5&nbsp;mg prednisone</strong> as the reference dose and
                assign each drug a potency factor relative to hydrocortisone =
                1. For example:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Hydrocortisone: potency ≈ 1 (20&nbsp;mg = 1 unit)</li>
                <li>
                  Prednisone / prednisolone: potency ≈ 4 (5&nbsp;mg = 1 unit)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Methylprednisolone / triamcinolone: potency ≈ 5 (4&nbsp;mg = 1
                  unit)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Dexamethasone / betamethasone: potency ≈ 25–30 (0.75&nbsp;mg =
                  1 unit)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>The algorithm is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong
                    >Step 1 – Convert input dose to hydrocortisone‑equivalent
                    units</strong
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  Let \( D_{\text{in}} \) be the input dose (mg/day) and \(
                  P_{\text{in}} \) the potency relative to hydrocortisone.
                </p>
                <p class="font-mono">units = D_in × P_in / 20</p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Step 2 – Convert units to target drug dose</strong>
                </p>
                <p>For each target drug with potency \( P_{\text{out}} \):</p>
                <p class="font-mono">D_out (mg/day) = units × 20 / P_out</p>
              </div>

              <h3>Clinical caveats and limitations</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Equivalence values are <strong>approximate</strong> and based
                  on average adult responses.
                </li>
                <li>
                  They apply primarily to
                  <strong>oral or IV systemic therapy</strong> at usual
                  anti‑inflammatory doses.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Topical, inhaled, intra‑articular, and ophthalmic preparations
                  have different potency relationships.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Half‑life, protein binding, and receptor kinetics differ
                  between drugs and may matter clinically.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Mineralocorticoid activity (salt‑retaining effect) is not
                  fully captured by glucocorticoid potency alone.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">
                Sources include standard endocrinology and pharmacology
                references, major clinical calculators, and published
                corticosteroid comparison tables. Values have been rounded for
                usability.
              </p>

              <h2>When to use a corticosteroid conversion</h2>
              <p>
                Common scenarios where a conversion table or calculator is
                helpful include:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Switching from IV methylprednisolone to oral prednisone at
                  hospital discharge.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Changing from prednisone to dexamethasone for specific
                  indications (e.g., cerebral edema, COVID‑19 protocols).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Converting chronic hydrocortisone replacement to an equivalent
                  prednisone dose (or vice versa).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Comparing total glucocorticoid exposure across different
                  regimens in research or audit work.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Even with a calculator,
                <strong>clinical judgment is essential</strong>. Tapering
                schedules, comorbidities, drug interactions, and
                patient‑specific factors must be considered.
              </p>
            </section>

