                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Does the route of administration matter?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Yes. The table and calculator are intended for
                    <strong>systemic oral or IV dosing</strong>. Bioavailability
                    and local potency can differ substantially for topical,
                    inhaled, intra‑articular, or ophthalmic formulations, so
                    separate reference data should be used for those routes.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can I use this to design a steroid taper?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    You can use the equivalence to estimate the total
                    glucocorticoid exposure, but tapering schedules depend on
                    duration of therapy, underlying disease, and risk of adrenal
                    suppression. Tapers should be designed and supervised by a
                    clinician familiar with the patient.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Why do some references list slightly different values?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Different sources may use different study populations,
                    endpoints (e.g., anti‑inflammatory vs. HPA axis
                    suppression), or rounding conventions. Differences are
                    usually small (e.g., 0.6 vs. 0.75&nbsp;mg dexamethasone).
                    This calculator uses a commonly accepted consensus set of
                    values.
                  </p>
                </details>
